"Verdes P.F.","Global Warming Is Driven by Anthropogenic Emissions: A Time Series Analysis Approach",2007,"Physical Review Letters","99","4", 048501,"","",,,10.1103/PhysRevLett.99.048501,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-34547453936&partnerID=40&md5=573ee74010d6e800dc01d637023d0276","Heidelberg Academy of Sciences, C/o Institute of Environmental Physics, Im Neuenheimer Feld 229, D-69120 Heidelberg, Germany","Verdes, P.F., Heidelberg Academy of Sciences, C/o Institute of Environmental Physics, Im Neuenheimer Feld 229, D-69120 Heidelberg, Germany","The solar influence on global climate is nonstationary. Processes such as the Schwabe and Gleissberg cycles of the Sun, or the many intrinsic atmospheric oscillation modes, yield a complex pattern of interaction with multiple time scales. In addition, emissions of greenhouse gases, aerosols, or volcanic dust perturb the dynamics of this coupled system to different and still uncertain extents. Here we show, using two independent driving force reconstruction techniques, that the combined effect of greenhouse gases and aerosol emissions has been the main external driver of global climate during the past decades. © 2007 The American Physical Society.",,"Aerosols; Dust; Earth atmosphere; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Sun; Volcanoes; Anthropogenic Emissions; Atmospheric oscillation modes; Force reconstruction; Global climate; Volcanic dust; Particulate emissions",,,,,,"(2001) IPCC Third Assessment Report-Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis, , edited by J.T. Houghton et al. (Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, England; Lean, J.L., Beer, J., Bradley, R.S., (1995) Geophys. Res. Lett., 22, p. 3195. , GPRLAJ 0094-8276 10.1029/95GL03093; Robertson, A., (2001) J. Geophys. Res., 106, p. 14783. , JGREA2 0148-0227 10.1029/2000JD900469; Shindell, D.T., Miller, R.L., Schmidt, G.A., Pandolfo, L., (1999) Nature (London), 399, p. 452. , NATUAS 0028-0836 10.1038/20905; Crowley, T., (2000) Science, 289, p. 270. , SC